U.S. Gasoline Demand Falls 1.8% From Last Year, MasterCard Says

-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 
2011-06-28T18:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-28/u-s-gasoline-demand-falls-1-8-from-last-year-mastercard-says.html
U.S. gasoline demand dipped 1.8
percent below year-earlier levels as pump prices were 32 percent
higher than in 2010, according to  MasterCard Inc. (MA)   Motorists bought an average 9.33 million barrels a day in
the week ended June 24, MasterCard said in its SpendingPulse
report. Consumption was 0.2 percent lower than the prior week,
the second-biggest payments network company said.  Averaged over four weeks, gasoline use was 0.2 percent
below the same period in 2010, John Gamel, director of economic
analysis for SpendingPulse, said in the report. It was the 14th
consecutive decline in the four-week average, Gamel said.  The average pump price declined 7 cents from the previous
week to $3.62 a gallon. Average retail prices are 32 percent
above a year earlier, according to the report.  The report from Purchase, New York-based MasterCard is
assembled by MasterCard Advisors, the companyâ€™s consulting arm.
The information is based on credit-card swipes and cash and
check payments at about 140,000 U.S. gasoline stations.  Visa Inc. (V)  is the biggest payments network company by
transactions processed.  To contact the reporter on this story:
